h side of Chicago (Roseland) and no one ever expects someone like me to emerge from that neighborhood.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:00:09','2013-10-28 22:00:09',3),(203,0,'Sharing all the photos on your device in an alternative format than Facebook, Flicker, and Instagram. \nHaving an old school photo-book that you can either carry in your briefcase (purse), or have as a conversation piece on your coffee table. Also, all photos can be stored in our \'cloud\' to save space on your device and as a back up in case of natural disaster.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:00:29','2013-10-28 22:00:29',4),(204,0,'No',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:00:30','2013-10-28 22:00:30',5),(205,0,'An amazing UX, WOM, testimonials, and various social media platforms.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:02:19','2013-10-28 22:02:19',6),(206,0,'Scott L. Steward, a 18-time award-winning teacher of entrepreneurship, expertise is frequently sought after by various publications. A former contributing writer for Chicagos NDIGO Magapaper, he provides tips on entrepreneurial ventures and suggestions for emerging entrepreneurs. In addition, Scott authored a business plan that is featured in the book, Make $1,000 in 35 days, is a contributor to the textbook, Entrepreneurship: Owning Your FUTURE 11th Edition, (Pearson, Prentice Hall), and author of 31 Ways to Improve Your Life: a Book of Stewismss (A Right Now Publishing).\n\nNow Interim Director of the Small Business Development Center at Chicago State University, CEO of Break Bread Marketing & Media, a boutique multimedia production company and marketing consulting firm, Master Certified Teacher of Entrepreneurship by the National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship (NFTE), and Professor of Small Business Management and Entrepreneurship at Chicago State University.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:03:35','2013-10-28 22:03:35',2),(207,0,'Taking the photos from your mobile device and delivering a photo-book to your doorstep in three easy steps. \n\nIn a few easy steps and at an affordable price, consumers can simply move their mobile photos from their phone into a tangible format that can serve as a keepsake and share-able product',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:04:17','2013-10-28 22:04:17',1),(208,0,'Photos stuck on a mobile device, lack of storage on a phone because of photos, and losing images if device is lost or stolen.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:05:57','2013-10-28 22:05:57',7),(209,0,'In a few easy steps and at an affordable price, consumers can simply move their mobile photos from their phone into a tangible format that can serve as a keepsake and share-able product. Also, all photos can be stored in our \'cloud\' to save space on your device and as a back up in case of natural disaster.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:06:06','2013-10-28 22:06:06',8),(210,0,'Six months ago.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:06:16','2013-10-28 22:06:16',10),(211,0,'Three weeks ago.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:06:26','2013-10-28 22:06:26',11),(212,0,'Now through December, identify programmers.\nDecember through June, create MVP.\nJune through December 2014, test MVP.\nJanuary 2015 launch.\nAcquired by December 2016',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:08:14','2013-10-28 22:08:14',9),(213,0,'Yes',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:08:23','2013-10-28 22:08:23',12),(214,0,'No',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:08:25','2013-10-28 22:08:25',13),(215,0,'200',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:08:47','2013-10-28 22:08:47',16),(216,0,'$20,000.00 USD',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:09:00','2013-10-28 22:09:00',15),(217,0,'1',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:09:07','2013-10-28 22:09:07',20),(218,0,'1',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:09:48','2013-10-28 22:09:48',18),(219,0,'To preserve people\'s memories.',NULL,34,'2013-10-28 22:10:58','2013-10-28 22:10:58',21),(220,1,'TripMob will acquire users through: 1. partnerships 2. endorsements from influencers 3.social media advertising.  Partnerships will be with online travel sites, and involve cross-promotional advertising, as well as affiliate revenue deals with the sites.  Endorsements from travel influencers will be obtained via CPA deals.  Finally our online advertising strategy will include heavy spends in SEM, Facebook advertising, and Pinterest marketing firm  HelloSociety.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:47:48','2013-11-18 08:20:35',6),(221,1,'Yes',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:47:48','2013-11-18 08:20:35',5),(222,1,'TripMob will acquire users through: 1. partnerships 2. endorsements from influencers 3.social media advertising.  Partnerships will be with online travel sites, and involve cross-promotional advertising, as well as affiliate revenue deals with the sites.  Endorsements from travel influencers will be obtained via CPA deals.  Finally our online advertising strategy will include heavy spends in SEM, Facebook advertising, and Pinterest marketing firm  HelloSociety.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:47:50','2013-11-18 08:20:20',4),(223,1,'Our idea is not unique as we have direct competitors.  What will separate us from those businesses is our customer acquisition strategy.  Weve spent a lot of time looking at our competition. and seen own missteps.  While their products are good in concept, we found the UX and UI clunky with a lot of room for improvement.  We found the scope of their product limited, and not as comprehensive as we plan.  Our ideas regarding affiliate marketing and upfront partnerships will differentiate us.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:47:52','2013-11-18 08:10:56',3),(224,2,'Georgie and Nicky met at business school at UCLA in 2011 and connected over a passion for startups. \n\nNicky grew up in Manchester, U.K. and now lives in Santa Monica building a VC-backed startup. Nicky has held leadership roles in two other seed/Series-A funded startups as well as experience as an associate in a prominent VC firm.  Across these startups he has raised over a million dollars in funding.  Prior to business school, Nicky worked in London in investment banking as well as in Hyderabad, India as a strategic consultant.\n\nGeorgie hails from Maryland, USA, attended UCLA business school and also lives and works in Santa Monica.   He works at a VC firm, not only making investment decisions but also acting as an entrepreneur-in-residence directly involved in portfolio companies\' operations. Directly prior to business school, George built and subsequently sold his own small business, and worked several years in banking and private equity in NYC.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:47:53','2013-11-18 08:02:03',2),(225,2,'Traveling with friends is one of lifes greatest adventures.  Organizing this trip, however, is a terrifyingly administrative and mundane project.  The average ten-person trip to a foreign destination involves 200 emails, 2400 instant messenger pings, 45 phone calls, 300 SMS texts, 8 voice mails and 5 online management tools. TripMob better organizes group travel by bringing all these management and communication tools into one place so all group members can make efficient decisions together.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:48:05','2013-11-18 08:07:56',1),(226,2,'We made the decision to pursue this after we were made aware of the 500Hrs program.  We both thought TripMob has extreme potential, but were getting held up by our lack of technical expertise.  The 500Hrs program has eliminated that roadblock, and given us the confidence to pursue this idea.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:50:01','2013-11-18 08:27:11',11),(227,1,'We came up with this after recently trying to organize a group trip to Austin City Limits, and becoming extremely frustrated with having to coordinate everyone\'s itineraries/housing/meals etc through a decentralized process.  There had to be a better way that could integrate into the way people already plan for their trips.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:50:02','2013-11-18 08:43:15',10),(228,1,'TripMobs 3 year roadmap will be as follows.  In year 1, the focus will be twofold - 1. product development and 2. user acquisition.  The product development side will involve building out an MVP of the product, and then testing that MVP out in real world settings to ensure that there is a fit between what features are being offered and what users actually want to use.  As the product develops, we will focus on best practices for user acquisition.  In year 1 this focus will be heavily on online advertising via Google, Facebook, and heavily trafficked, travel related sites.  This will allow to optimize our content for ad copy, and figure out which channels get us users at the lowest cost per acquisition.  Luckily our product is inherently social and viral because it is meant to be shared and used by groups.  Year 2 of the product will focus extensively on building out our partnership relationships.  As Year 1 will hopefully have enabled us to fully understand our target customer while building up a large user-base, we will leverage the size of that user-base to then approach the same travel sites we were advertising on to build partnerships.  With a strong enough product and high user engagement statistics, it is likely that several of these sites might be interested.  Finally year 3 will continue to be similar to year 2.  A focus on business development will continue and hopefully partnerships made in year 2 will allow for the credibility needed to establish even more partnerships in year 3.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:50:04','2013-11-18 08:58:09',9),(229,1,'The 500Hrs program would enable us to effectively solve the problems outlined from the previous question.  Our lack of technical expertise was a major stumbling point in progressing this idea forward.  However if we were able to win this competition, this would allow us to build out a MVP to test the concept, gain a userbase that provides feedback, and incorporate those revisions within the product.  If we did not win the competition, there are ways that we can solve these problems in a non-tech way.  Instead of a fully functional MVP, we would be able to construct clickable wireframes that would allow the general functionality of the site to be demonstrated.  After constructing these wireframes using a service like Balsamiq, we would be able to run smaller test groups with users we could find through our own network.  We can also run design iterations by surveying a large group of random people via Mechanical Turk.  Finally we can constantly upgrade our design and functionality via our wireframes before having the site built for us through a third party development agency.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:50:06','2013-11-18 08:41:58',8),(230,1,'The top 3 problems Tripmob has faced during product development include 1. building out an MVP of the product 2. gaining a beta userbase to test and provide feedback on an MVP 3. incorporating that feedback to iterate different versions of the product and launch a version that would gain traction with the general public.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:50:07','2013-11-18 08:25:03',7),(231,0,'Yes',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:51:51','2013-10-28 23:51:51',12),(232,1,'Yes',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:51:52','2013-11-18 08:58:12',13),(233,1,'500',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:51:58','2013-11-18 08:58:35',16),(234,1,'$7,500',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:51:59','2013-11-18 08:58:50',15),(235,0,'0',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:52:18','2013-10-28 23:52:18',20),(236,1,'2',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:52:46','2013-11-18 08:58:57',17),(237,0,'2',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:52:48','2013-10-28 23:52:48',18),(238,1,'We have been searching for the opportunity to start a new, scale-able tech company together.   The opportunity to work on something that we both have experienced frustration with fuels us both to execute on the vision for TripMob.  Also our collective previous working experiences at larger corporations have ingrained in us a drive to not be stuck in the bureaucracy of a larger  company, and start our own company where we can have a direct impact on the operations and culture of the company.',NULL,33,'2013-10-28 23:53:09','2013-11-18 09:07:06',21),(239,1,'https://www.dropbox.com/s/30in8b898nwquor/TripMob%203.pptx',NULL,33,'2013-10-29 00:24:33','2013-11-26 04:02:33',19),(240